              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Sleppen</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;06/01/2003&nbsp;: 07:40:39 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> I've been away from the boards for a couple days except for brief visits, but I can handle the question posed by our cleric friend:<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">So why should Necros be able to solo comparable content to what the non-solo classes need a group to kill? Answer that to my satisfaction and I'll gladly leave this board forever...<br /><br />and saying because necros are a solo class is not a valid answer.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I'll give you two answers, both of which are valid.<br /><br />Answer one: you are operating off of an inaccurate stereotype of soloists.  For the most part, soloists do not kill the same mobs that are killed by groups of comparable level, gear, and skill.  Please keep the "comparable level, gear, and skill" part in mind.  Just because you see some level 65 necromancer with 300 AAs from Fires of Triton's Afterlife soloing Thug Ubersmasher in the Plane of Phat Lewtz does not make that a valid basis for comparison to much of anything.  You need to compare apples to apples.<br /><br />Answer two: you have an inaccurate stereotype of groups.  Simply stated, groups tend to slum and kill mobs that are beneath their capabilities.  Furthermore, many groups are intensely conservative and unwilling to take risks.  You can see 60ish groups killing mobs at the zone-in in Plane of Innovation.  Although a cleric may "need" a group to kill those mobs, the cleric's group is capable of doing much better in terms of XP, loot, and excitement.  Just because there is overlap between the range of mobs actually killed by soloists and groups of comparable level does not mean much of anything.<br /><br />With those two points in mind, let's return to your question: "why should Necros be able to solo comparable content to what the non-solo classes need a group to kill?"  The answer is that necros cannot do that, with a small number of exceptions.  A level 61 necromancer cannot solo comparable content to what a similarly equipped group consisting of a level 61 warrior, cleric, enchanter, etc. can kill.  I can say that definitively because I actually play a level 61 warrior and a level 61 necromancer.<br /><br />If the level 61 necromancer is killing the same mobs as the level 61 group, it means one of two things.  First, the level 61 necromancer is not comparable due to superior gear or skill, or the level 61 necromancer is taking risks that are much greater than are being taken by the group.  (When you see necromancers say that they haven't died in months, bear in mind that those are not the people who do high-risk soloing.)  Second, the group is slumming and killing mobs that are substantially below its capabilities, or the group simply lacks the skill level or experience to handle camps that are more suitable to its power level.<br /><br />I freely admit that there are a small number of exceptions to what I just said.  However, nerfing overall soloist XP is not the way to address those exceptions.  The typical level 57ish necromancer soloing rats in Plane of Disease should not suffer because some high end necromancer has found a way to make exceptional experience.  (BTW, when was the last time you saw a high 50s group killing flies or rats in PoD?  Groups don't kill those mobs because they can do better in PoP, and that is my point.  I often see level 60 and 61 soloists killing those very mobs.)<br /><br />So my answer to your question boils down to this: your question makes false assumptions about soloists and groups and assumes a level of equality that does not exist in the game.  If there are specific situations in which soloing experience is excessive (based on an apples to apples comparison and taking into account risk/reward), then those specific situations should be addressed.  Nerfing overall soloing XP is the wrong solution.<br /><br />Note: I started writing this last night, but went to bed before finishing it.  While I was sleeping, Etadanik wrote his excellent post that makes the same point with a different spin.  Nice post, Etadanik.</span></font></td>
              </tr>
